            <p>
                Nuclear and fossil fuel power stations are very similar - the energy source is used to heat water and produce
                steam which creates pressure and turns turbines. These turbines turn magnets creating an electromagnetic
                field thus generating electricity. This is a good example of energy transfer between stores;
                <u>chemical -> heat -> kinetic -> electrical</u>.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- PART 5 -->
        <div class=""tab-pane fade"" id=""part5"">
            <br />
            <p><strong>Renewable energy</strong></p>
            <br />
            <p>
                Renewable energy sources are defined by their ability to generate ");
            WriteLiteral(@"energy whilst they themselves are not
                running out. Countries around the world have different methods to generate energy based upon their geography.
                Renewable technologies include;
                <ul>
                    <li>Bio-fuel;</li>
                    <li>Geothermal;</li>
                    <li>Hydroelectricity;</li>
                    <li>Tides;</li>
                    <li>The Sun;</li>
                    <li>Wave;</li>
                    <li>Wind.</li>
                </ul>
            </p>
            <p>
                While these energies do not generate carbon emissions, the installation of these devices can do a lot of
                damage to the environment, or ongoing damage to the ecosystem after installation. Furthermore, individual
                platforms don't often generate that much energy, and so multiple platforms have to be installed to meet
                the demands of the modern world.
            </p>
        </div>
");
            WriteLiteral(@"
        <!-- PART 6 -->
        <div class=""tab-pane fade"" id=""part6"">
            <br />
            <p><strong>Renewable energy</strong></p>
            <br />
            <p>
                <b>Bio-fuels</b> are considered renewable, however their use is still not fully justified to the scientific
                community. Bio-fuels are a biologically made source of fuel; animal dung, crops or fire wood. The carbon
                released from using these products as fuel is thought to be re-absorbed by the plants that are planted in
                place of the burnt products. The problem with bio-fuels is that they take large volumes of time, space and
                water, and are not a viable energy source for the world on their own.
