                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                <b>Hydroelectric</b>, <b>tidal</b> and <b>wave</b> power are often confused with one another.
                Wave power uses devices that sit on the surface of the sea, and as they bob up and down with the
                movement of the waves, a coil of wire moves around a generator. The tidal form often uses a barrage
                of turbines that sit beneath the sea - as the tide moves in and out, this volume of water turns the
                turbines generating electricity but the tides are so accurately forecasted where other forms of
                energy are difficult to predict. Hydroelectricity uses large volumes of water that are either held
                behind a dam, or falling from an elevated position (waterfall or mountainous river) that turn
     ");
            WriteLiteral(@"           turbines. These forms of energy often cause damage to the surrounding environment, cause flooding
                or disturb creatures in their natural environments.
            </p>
