            WriteLiteral(@"
                            <figcaption>Photo by Pixabay from Pexels</figcaption>
                        </figure>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <p>
                The tricky part of using renewable energies is pre-empting when the country needs to use this energy.
                For instance, it's well known that during tv advert breaks in the evening, the country would often
                see a surge in the need for energy due to the amounts of tea being brewed. Renewable energies are
                difficult to harvest predictably, and currently unable to be stored whilst fossil and nuclear fuels
                can be fired when needed to generate electricity. It's a difficult line to tread.
            </p>
        </div>

        <!-- SUMMARY 1 -->
        <div class=""tab-pane fade"" id=""summary1"">
            <br />
            <p><strong>Summary 1</strong></p>
            <br />
            <ul>
                <li>
       ");
            WriteLiteral(@"             There are three forms of energy transfer; <b>conduction</b>, <b>convection</b>, and <b>radiation</b>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Conduction means particles with higher temperature sharing their heat energy with particles that have a less heat
                    energy.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Good conductors of heat are typically solids - often metals.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Poor conductors of heat are typically liquids and gases.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Convection is found in fluids (liquids and gases).
                </li>
                <li>
                    As a fluid heats up, it becomes less dense and rises, being replaced by cold air and causing a convection current.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Conduction and convection rely on something coming into contact with the source of hea");
            WriteLiteral(@"t (frying pan or radiator).
                </li>
                <li>
                    Radiation is energy emitted in the form of electromagnetic waves - infra-red, ultraviolet or visible light.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Radiation does not require matter to exchange heat - the Sun produces vast quantities of EM radiation that reaches us
                    through the vaccuum of space.
                </li>
            </ul>
        </div>

        <!-- SUMMARY 2 -->
        <div class=""tab-pane fade"" id=""summary2"">
            <br />
            <p><strong>Summary 2</strong></p>
            <br />
            <ul>
                <li>
                    Non-renewable energy sources include fossil fuels and nuclear energy.
                </li>
                <li>
                    These energy sources once used, cannot be re-used and are often good for meeting short term energy demands.
                </li>
                <li>
          ");
            WriteLiteral(@"          The by-products of fossil fuels are CO<sub>2</sub> and other emissions which are accelerating climate change.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The exploration for and mining of fossil fuels are often damaging to the environment.
                </li>
                <li>
                    The by-products of nuclear energy is often just water vapour, although spent fuel rods are difficult to store.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Renewable energy sources are those that can provide energy to us whilst they also are not running out.
                </li>
                <li>
                    These sources are <b>Bio-fuel</b>, <b>Geothermal</b>, <b>Hydroelectricity</b>, <b>Tidal</b>,
                    <b>Solar</b>, <b>Wave</b> and <b>Wind</b>.
                </li>
                <li>
                    Some of the renewable energy sources still cause destruction to the environment, but they are not
                  ");
            WriteLiteral("  accelerating the rate of climate change or releasing vast quantities of carbon emissions.\r\n                </li>\r\n            </ul>\r\n            <hr />\r\n            ");
            EndContext();
